to make it more convenient, the moral effect of the present law regulating this department of our propaganda
will be destroyed because violated. From information coming through correspondence I draw these conclusions,
that the comrades appreciate the value of our law to protect the organization against "free lancing," but seem
to object to it because of the intervention of the third party, which makes it more or less cumbersome to
them. The recent referendum was sustained simply because the locals did not wish to abolish the law in
its entirety, but it must be understood that the comrades do not all approve of the law as it now stands.
It was only for fear that we would again revert back to the wild-cat, free-lancing methods which were ex-
perienced in former years that this law was not repealed. As a substitute for the present law 1 would rec-
ommend to this convention that the law be so revised that it will be more agreeable to the locals as well
as to the speakers, and at the same time protect our organization. All speakers should have the endorsement
of the State Executive Committee, who should review the qualiﬁcations and fitness of such speakers, then
we can consider such a settled matter, then when any local wishes to have speakers, that they select those
that they might prefer from this list of duly qualiﬁed speakeis and after the agreement has been made
between the local and the speaker as to date, etc., that the State ofﬁce should then be notified by both speak-
er as well as the local so as to avoid any conflict in date. At the same time this will afford the state See-
retary an opportunity to reach any speaker at any time when it becomes necessary. This is the only demo-
cratic way in dealing with the speakers, and it avoids any partiality on the part of the State officials in
the routing of certain speakers. Besides, the speakers will feel a responsibility, knowing that he or she
must have the endorsement of the State Executive Committee in order to work within the State. It gives
the local an opportunity to also satisfy their own desires and the State is not to blame if the meetings do not
prove a success. At the present time there are many speakers on the available list, which proves the interest
taken in this department of our work. On ‘August ﬁrst there were but four speakers on the available list,
and it was necessary to advertise in The Bulletin that speakers were needed. This list has steadily grown
until there are now nineteen whose names and addresses are published in The Bulletin. it is the wish of
the State office that we encourage our local State speakers by assisting them whenever possible, but it be-
comes necessary at times that we employ speakers irom outside the State. There is a diversity of opinion
as to whether the sub-plan or the regular plan of routing speakers is. the better, and from .all indications 1
would suggest that it is best to permit‘ this to run its course so long as it does not conﬂict with the laws
regulating speakers.

Organization and Political suggestions.

Since there are a great many differences on the question of organization, and most all being good and‘

well intended, I feel that it is best to leave this matter to the Committee‘on Organization and Propaganda.
However, it might be in order to suggest that a Standing Committee on By-Laws and Platform be elected
and that this committee attend to this particular duty alone. This committee should be limited to two or
three so as to eliminate the danger of losing such documents, as much as possible, through mailing, if the
work is to be done by correspondence. ' .

Besides the possibilities of losing these valuable papers, the sending of such bulky matter by mail is too
cumbersome. It must also be realized that it would be impossible to send all of the various platforms and
by-laws over the State through the mails. With the great movement that we now have and which is ever
growing, comes with it the necessary changes in order to meet the requirements of, and which are neces-
sary for the proper conducting of our affairs. The above proposition can be facilitated in three different
ways—by a committee elected bythe membership to attend to such duties, or that a sub-committee elected
by the members of the State Executive Committee from that body, but it seems to me that there should be
a code to cover at least the principal requirements of our party, this to be made universal, but it should be
so drawn up that those questions relating to local affairs can be added, providing such items do not conﬂict
with the provisions of our constitution.

Assistance is also solicited by the State office in the matter of getting up a list of simpliﬁed instruc-
tions to guide the many inquirers seeking information as to how to proceed to get their tickets in the ﬁeld
in accordance with the provisions of the new primary law, and such other matters that will assist the party
membership along this line.

' - rlnanolal conditions of the State Organization.

On August 1, 1910, after the committee—Comradees Dan P. Farrell and Joseph Quill—had~audited the
books, a balance of ninety-two dollars and seventy-one cents ($92.71) was declared, but there were outstand-
ing bills enough to reduce -this amount to forty—one dollars and ninety-three cents ($41.93) deﬁcit against the
treaury after all bills were paid. This indebtedness was disposed of and the funds have steadily increased
until -we have reached the sum of $1',060 surplus in the State treasury up to April 1; It is hoped that this
amount will be used in the great. ﬁght that is before us in this State during the coming campaign.

It is the opinion of the State Secretary that the enemy will concentrate its forces to ﬁght our movement -

in Ohioon account of the progress that our party has made. Our treasury is at present in a healthy con-
dition to at least afford us a means of resistance in the next campaign. This ought to be used for the purpose
of getting out literature-and speakers to cover the entire State. -

The next ﬁght will be the hardest battle ever waged by our party in this State and our funds ought to
be used principally for this purpose. ‘

