Resolution No. 8.

MUNICIPAL PROGRAM
Adopted by the Ohio State Convention,
April 30, 1911. \

The ﬁrst consideration in all municipal affairs
should be the interests of the working class. The
Socialist Party is not organized to elect good men
to office, but to-control the powers of political gov-
ernment in order to guarantee to the workers the
possession and operation of the means of produc-
tion and distribution and the full social product
of their labor. Various issues will arise in the
communities of Ohio, and the Socialist Party stands
ﬁrmly for the rights 0 the producing class. The
party daclares: . ,

1. For the initiative, referendum and recall in
municipal affairs. '

2. The public ownership of all public utilities.
For the abolishing of the contract system in pub-
lic improvements and the doing of all such work
by the municipality direct.

3. For the eight-hour day, for all laborers em-
ployed on public improvements and in municipal
departments. ' I '

4. For the rigid inspection of workshops, fac-
tories and places of public assembly.

For the enforcement of the laws to protect
the lives of workers while. engaged in industries.

6. For the best sanitary conditions in tenements
and elsewhere. .

7. For parks and playgrounds located within
reach of the workers.

For free text-books in public schools.

9. For the free administration of justice, and
the appointment of a public “de"ender” as well as
a prosecutor, as at present. ‘ '

The enforcement of the legal requirements
as to weights and measures. R
