It is not my wish to reflect in any way upon the past by showing up the present condition of. our State
movement. My better judgment tells me that all secretaries must have had a just-pride in ‘the accom-
plishments of their respective administrations. All have worked hard of course, some harder than others,
but as ,a rule all have done well under existing circumstances. ’

The task of serving a revolutionary organization can only be realized when we are acting in some ca-
pacity or are in responsible positions of such an organization. Whatever has been accomplished within the
last nine months just passed, was done in the spirit of co-operation and good will, and which did not depend
upon the superior qualiﬁcations of your State Executive Committee nor any individual, nor did it depend
upon anyindividual local within the State, but it was by united and concerted action of all the members, the
unusual activity of the Socialist press, the lecturers and campaigners, but best of all the committees of agi-
tators and workers in the movement. This has brought Ohio to the fore as the greatest Socialist State in
the Union. There is not another State in the Union that can compare with Ohio in a more even distribution
of locals over the State. All this was done. by the comrades in the spirit of duty to one another, the State
and to the Nation. .

Accomplishments.

Beginning April 1st, 1910, up to August 1st, nineteen. locals were organized. These were taken in during
the administration of former or acting State Secretary Comrade E. E. Adel. Beginning August 1st to April
27th, 1911, 91 locals were taken in, averaging ten locals per month for the past nine months. A great num-
ber of these locals were organized by Comrade A. B. Shinn, who was employed as organizer in the unor-
ganized territory most of the time, and who is now devoting part of his time to this work. About ten of
this total number of locals could not weather the storms of capitalism and dropped out, leaving about 81
of the new locals to aid in the ﬁnal overthrow of capitalism. This is a result of the last nine months’ work.
The membership has steadily increased and the reported number of members afﬁliated with the organiza-
tion reach nearly 6,500. There are now all told 190 locals in the State. ~

Importance of Ohio Socialist Bulletin.

The Ohio Socialist Bulletin is a necessary appendage to our State organization and has grown to such
importance that most locals insist -on having,a full quota of copies, and usually make it known when an in-
sufficient number has been sent out to supply the members of their locals. .However, there is a consider-
able amount of labor connected with it and the expense of mailing it has become quite an item, the size has
been incrased from six to eight pages within the last eight or nine months and the number of copies printed
for distribution has increased from 3,500 to 5,500 copies per month. An effort was made to have it admitted
for second—class mailing privileges, but the postoflice ofﬁcials could not consider the proposition unless some
popular subscription price be placed upon it; in other words, they insist that The Bulletin must have some
intrinsic value of its own. If suggestions are in order relative to this matter I would recommend that the
convention take up this question so as to make it possible to take advantage of the privileges allowed to
other publications, as well as organizations. To abolish The Bulletin would really be foolish and would
meet with universal disapproval by our party membership in Ohio. .

